{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$path='\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.1.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-review-all-gdds.md'; \"'$lines=Get-Content $path; for($n=118;$n -le 477;$n++){ '\"'{0,4}: {1}' -f \"'$n, $lines[$n-1] }'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$i=1; Get-Content '\"'verification/fixtures/gdds/combat.md' | ForEach-Object { '{0,4}: {1}' -f \"'$i, $_; $i++ }'","aggregated_output":"   1: # Combat System\r\n   2: \r\n   3: ## Overview\r\n   4: \r\n   5: Combat is an optional defensive system used when storms create hostile echoes.\r\n   6: \r\n   7: ## Player Fantasy\r\n   8: \r\n   9: The player survives through preparation and readable counterplay.\r\n  10: \r\n  11: ## Detailed Design\r\n  12: \r\n  13: - Each defeated echo awards 20 gold.\r\n  14: - On death, the player loses 25% of current gold.\r\n  15: - A single hit cannot reduce a full-health player below 1 health.\r\n  16: \r\n  17: ## Formulas\r\n  18: \r\n  19: `damage = base_damage * power_multiplier`\r\n  20: \r\n  21: - `base_damage`: 10-40\r\n  22: - `power_multiplier`: 1-5\r\n  23: - Output: 10-200 damage\r\n  24: \r\n  25: ## Dependencies\r\n  26: \r\n  27: - Outputs kill rewards to Economy.\r\n  28: - Reads the Economy-owned death-loss percentage.\r\n  29: \r\n  30: ## Tuning Knobs\r\n  31: \r\n  32: - `kill_gold_reward = 20` 鈥?owned by Combat.\r\n  33: - `death_gold_loss_percent = 25` 鈥?owned by Combat.\r\n  34: \r\n  35: ## Acceptance Criteria\r\n  36: \r\n  37: - GIVEN full health, WHEN one attack lands, THEN the player retains at least 1 health.\r\n  38: - GIVEN an echo dies, WHEN its reward resolves, THEN Economy receives 20 gold.\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_19","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$i=1; Get-Content '\"'verification/fixtures/gdds/economy.md' | ForEach-Object { '{0,4}: {1}' -f \"'$i, $_; $i++ }'","aggregated_output":"   1: # Economy System\r\n   2: \r\n   3: ## Overview\r\n   4: \r\n   5: Gold buys expedition consumables and permanent lantern upgrades.\r\n   6: \r\n   7: ## Player Fantasy\r\n   8: \r\n   9: Every successful expedition creates a meaningful preparation choice.\r\n  10: \r\n  11: ## Detailed Design\r\n  12: \r\n  13: - Each defeated echo awards 10 gold.\r\n  14: - On death, the player loses 50% of current gold with no cap.\r\n  15: - Lantern upgrades cost gold and permanently increase damage resistance.\r\n  16: \r\n  17: ## Formulas\r\n  18: \r\n  19: `upgrade_cost = 50 * 2^tier`\r\n  20: \r\n  21: - `tier`: integer 0-8\r\n  22: - Output: 50-12,800 gold\r\n  23: \r\n  24: ## Dependencies\r\n  25: \r\n  26: - Receives a 10-gold kill reward from Combat.\r\n  27: - Economy defines and owns the death-loss percentage.\r\n  28: \r\n  29: ## Tuning Knobs\r\n  30: \r\n  31: - `kill_gold_reward = 10` 鈥?owned by Economy.\r\n  32: - `death_gold_loss_percent = 50` 鈥?owned by Economy.\r\n  33: \r\n  34: ## Acceptance Criteria\r\n  35: \r\n  36: - GIVEN any current gold balance, WHEN the player dies, THEN exactly 50% is removed.\r\n  37: - GIVEN an echo dies, WHEN its reward resolves, THEN the player receives 10 gold.\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$path='\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.1.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-review-all-gdds.md'; \"'$lines=Get-Content $path; for($n=118;$n -le 477;$n++){ '\"'{0,4}: {1}' -f \"'$n, $lines[$n-1] }'","aggregated_output":" 118: ## Phase 2: Cross-GDD Consistency\r\n 119: \r\n 120: Work through every pair and group of GDDs to find contradictions and gaps.\r\n 121: \r\n 122: ### 2a: Dependency Bidirectionality\r\n 123: \r\n 124: For every GDD's Dependencies section, check that every listed dependency is\r\n 125: reciprocal:\r\n 126: - If GDD-A lists \"depends on GDD-B\", check that GDD-B lists GDD-A as a dependent\r\n 127: - If GDD-A lists \"depended on by GDD-C\", check that GDD-C lists GDD-A as a dependency\r\n 128: - Flag any one-directional dependency as a consistency issue\r\n 129: \r\n 130: ```\r\n 131: 鈿狅笍  Dependency Asymmetry\r\n 132: [system-a].md lists: Depends On 鈫?[system-b].md\r\n 133: [system-b].md does NOT list [system-a].md as a dependent\r\n 134: 鈫?One of these documents has a stale dependency section\r\n 135: ```\r\n 136: \r\n 137: ### 2b: Rule Contradictions\r\n 138: \r\n 139: For each game rule, mechanic, or constraint defined in any GDD, check whether\r\n 140: any other GDD defines a contradicting rule for the same situation:\r\n 141: \r\n 142: Categories to scan:\r\n 143: - **Floor/ceiling rules**: Does any GDD define a minimum value for an output? Does any other say a different system can bypass that floor? These contradict.\r\n 144: - **Resource ownership**: If two GDDs both define how a shared resource accumulates or depletes, do they agree?\r\n 145: - **State transitions**: If GDD-A describes what happens when a character dies,\r\n 146:   does GDD-B's description of the same event agree?\r\n 147: - **Timing**: If GDD-A says \"X happens on the same frame\", does GDD-B assume\r\n 148:   it happens asynchronously?\r\n 149: - **Stacking rules**: If GDD-A says status effects stack, does GDD-B assume\r\n 150:   they don't?\r\n 151: \r\n 152: ```\r\n 153: 馃敶 Rule Contradiction\r\n 154: [system-a].md: \"Minimum [output] after reduction is [floor_value]\"\r\n 155: [system-b].md: \"[mechanic] bypasses [system-a]'s rules and can reduce [output] to 0\"\r\n 156: 鈫?These rules directly contradict. Which GDD is authoritative?\r\n 157: ```\r\n 158: \r\n 159: ### 2c: Stale References\r\n 160: \r\n 161: For every cross-document reference (GDD-A mentions a mechanic, value, or\r\n 162: system name from GDD-B), verify the referenced element still exists in GDD-B\r\n 163: with the same name and behaviour:\r\n 164: \r\n 165: - If GDD-A says \"combo multiplier from the combat system feeds into score\", check\r\n 166:   that the combat GDD actually defines a combo multiplier that outputs to score\r\n 167: - If GDD-A references \"the progression curve defined in [system].md\", check that\r\n 168:   [system].md actually has that curve, not a different progression model\r\n 169: - If GDD-A was written before GDD-B and assumed a mechanic that GDD-B later\r\n 170:   designed differently, flag GDD-A as containing a stale reference\r\n 171: \r\n 172: ```\r\n 173: 鈿狅笍  Stale Reference\r\n 174: inventory.md (written first): \"Item weight uses the encumbrance formula\r\n 175:   from movement.md\"\r\n 176: movement.md (written later): Defines no encumbrance formula 鈥?uses a flat\r\n 177:   carry limit instead\r\n 178: 鈫?inventory.md references a formula that doesn't exist\r\n 179: ```\r\n 180: \r\n 181: ### 2d: Data and Tuning Knob Ownership Conflicts\r\n 182: \r\n 183: Two GDDs should not both claim to own the same data or tuning knob. Scan all\r\n 184: Tuning Knobs sections across all GDDs and flag duplicates:\r\n 185: \r\n 186: ```\r\n 187: 鈿狅笍  Ownership Conflict\r\n 188: [system-a].md Tuning Knobs: \"[multiplier_name] 鈥?controls [output] scaling\"\r\n 189: [system-b].md Tuning Knobs: \"[multiplier_name] 鈥?scales [output] with [factor]\"\r\n 190: 鈫?Two GDDs define multipliers on the same output. Which owns the final value?\r\n 191:   This will produce either a double-application bug or a design conflict.\r\n 192: ```\r\n 193: \r\n 194: ### 2e: Formula Compatibility\r\n 195: \r\n 196: For GDDs whose formulas are connected (output of one feeds input of another),\r\n 197: check that the output range of the upstream formula is within the expected\r\n 198: input range of the downstream formula:\r\n 199: \r\n 200: - If [system-a].md outputs values between [min]鈥揫max], and [system-b].md is\r\n 201:   designed to receive values between [min2]鈥揫max2], is the mismatch intentional?\r\n 202: - If an economy GDD expects resource acquisition in range X, and the\r\n 203:   progression GDD generates it at range Y, the economy will be trivial or\r\n 204:   inaccessible 鈥?is that intended?\r\n 205: \r\n 206: Flag incompatibilities as CONCERNS (design judgment needed, not necessarily wrong):\r\n 207: \r\n 208: ```\r\n 209: 鈿狅笍  Formula Range Mismatch\r\n 210: [system-a].md: Max [output] = [value_a] (at max [condition])\r\n 211: [system-b].md: Base [input] = [value_b], max [input] = [value_c]\r\n 212: 鈫?Late-[stage] [scenario] can resolve in a single [event].\r\n 213:   Is this intentional? If not, either [system-a]'s ceiling or [system-b]'s ceiling needs adjustment.\r\n 214: ```\r\n 215: \r\n 216: ### 2f: Acceptance Criteria Cross-Check\r\n 217: \r\n 218: Scan Acceptance Criteria sections across all GDDs for contradictions:\r\n 219: \r\n 220: - GDD-A criteria: \"Player cannot die from a single hit\"\r\n 221: - GDD-B criteria: \"Boss attack deals 150% of player max health\"\r\n 222: These acceptance criteria cannot both pass simultaneously.\r\n 223: \r\n 224: ---\r\n 225: \r\n 226: ## Phase 3: Game Design Holism\r\n 227: \r\n 228: Review all GDDs together through the lens of game design theory and player\r\n 229: psychology. These are issues that individual GDD reviews cannot catch because\r\n 230: they require seeing all systems at once.\r\n 231: \r\n 232: ### 3a: Progression Loop Competition\r\n 233: \r\n 234: A game should have one dominant progression loop that players feel is \"the\r\n 235: point\" of the game, with supporting loops that feed into it. When multiple\r\n 236: systems compete equally as the primary progression driver, players don't know\r\n 237: what the game is about.\r\n 238: \r\n 239: Scan all GDDs for systems that:\r\n 240: - Award the player's primary resource (XP, levels, prestige, unlocks)\r\n 241: - Define themselves as the \"core\" or \"main\" loop\r\n 242: - Have comparable depth and time investment to other systems doing the same\r\n 243: \r\n 244: ```\r\n 245: 鈿狅笍  Competing Progression Loops\r\n 246: combat.md: Awards XP, unlocks abilities, is described as \"the core loop\"\r\n 247: crafting.md: Awards XP, unlocks recipes, is described as \"the primary activity\"\r\n 248: exploration.md: Awards XP, unlocks map areas, described as \"the main driver\"\r\n 249: 鈫?Three systems all claim to be the primary progression loop and all award\r\n 250:   the same primary currency. Players will optimise one and ignore the others.\r\n 251:   Consider: one primary loop with the others as support systems.\r\n 252: ```\r\n 253: \r\n 254: ### 3b: Player Attention Budget\r\n 255: \r\n 256: Count how many systems require active player attention simultaneously during\r\n 257: a typical session. Each actively-managed system costs attention:\r\n 258: \r\n 259: - Active = player must make decisions about this system regularly during play\r\n 260: - Passive = system runs automatically, player sees results but doesn't manage it\r\n 261: \r\n 262: More than 3-4 simultaneously active systems creates cognitive overload for most\r\n 263: players. Present the count and flag if it exceeds 4 concurrent active systems:\r\n 264: \r\n 265: ```\r\n 266: 鈿狅笍  Cognitive Load Risk\r\n 267: Simultaneously active systems during [core loop moment]:\r\n 268:   1. [system-a].md 鈥?[decision type] (active)\r\n 269:   2. [system-b].md 鈥?[resource management] (active)\r\n 270:   3. [system-c].md 鈥?[tracking] (active)\r\n 271:   4. [system-d].md 鈥?[item/action use] (active)\r\n 272:   5. [system-e].md 鈥?[cooldown/timer management] (active)\r\n 273:   6. [system-f].md 鈥?[coordination decisions] (active)\r\n 274: 鈫?6 simultaneously active systems during the core loop.\r\n 275:   Research suggests 3-4 is the comfortable limit for most players.\r\n 276:   Consider: which of these can be made passive or simplified?\r\n 277: ```\r\n 278: \r\n 279: ### 3c: Dominant Strategy Detection\r\n 280: \r\n 281: A dominant strategy makes other strategies irrelevant 鈥?players discover it,\r\n 282: use it exclusively, and find the rest of the game boring. Look for:\r\n 283: \r\n 284: - **Resource monopolies**: One strategy generates a resource significantly\r\n 285:   faster than all others\r\n 286: - **Risk-free power**: A strategy that is both high-reward and low-risk\r\n 287:   (if high-risk strategies exist, they need proportionally higher reward)\r\n 288: - **No trade-offs**: An option that is superior in all dimensions to all others\r\n 289: - **Obvious optimal path**: If any progression choice is \"clearly correct\",\r\n 290:   the others aren't real choices\r\n 291: \r\n 292: ```\r\n 293: 鈿狅笍  Potential Dominant Strategy\r\n 294: combat.md: Ranged attacks deal 80% of melee damage with no risk\r\n 295: combat.md: Melee attacks deal 100% damage but require close range\r\n 296: 鈫?Unless melee has a significant compensating advantage (AOE, stagger,\r\n 297:   resource regeneration), ranged is dominant 鈥?higher safety, only 20% less\r\n 298:   damage. Consider what melee offers that ranged cannot.\r\n 299: ```\r\n 300: \r\n 301: ### 3d: Economic Loop Analysis\r\n 302: \r\n 303: Identify all resources across all GDDs (gold, XP, crafting materials, stamina,\r\n 304: health, mana, etc.). For each resource, map its **sources** (how players gain\r\n 305: it) and **sinks** (how players spend it).\r\n 306: \r\n 307: Flag dangerous economic conditions:\r\n 308: \r\n 309: | Condition | Sign | Risk |\r\n 310: |-----------|------|------|\r\n 311: | **Infinite source, no sink** | Resource accumulates indefinitely | Late game becomes trivially easy |\r\n 312: | **Sink, no source** | Resource drains to zero | System becomes unavailable |\r\n 313: | **Source >> Sink** | Surplus accumulates | Resource becomes meaningless |\r\n 314: | **Sink >> Source** | Constant scarcity | Frustration and gatekeeping |\r\n 315: | **Positive feedback loop** | More resource 鈫?easier to earn more | Runaway leader, snowball |\r\n 316: | **No catch-up** | Falling behind accelerates deficit | Unrecoverable states |\r\n 317: \r\n 318: ```\r\n 319: 馃敶 Economic Imbalance: Unbounded Positive Feedback\r\n 320: gold economy:\r\n 321:   Sources: monster drops (scales with player power), merchant selling (unlimited)\r\n 322:   Sinks: equipment purchase (one-time), ability upgrades (finite count)\r\n 323: 鈫?After equipment and abilities are purchased, gold has no sink.\r\n 324:   Infinite surplus. Gold becomes meaningless mid-game.\r\n 325:   Add ongoing gold sinks (upkeep, consumables, cosmetics, gambling).\r\n 326: ```\r\n 327: \r\n 328: ### 3e: Difficulty Curve Consistency\r\n 329: \r\n 330: When multiple systems scale with player progression, they must scale in\r\n 331: compatible directions and at compatible rates. Mismatched scaling curves\r\n 332: create unintended difficulty spikes or trivialisations.\r\n 333: \r\n 334: For each system that scales over time, extract:\r\n 335: - What scales (enemy health, player damage, resource cost, area size)\r\n 336: - How it scales (linear, exponential, stepped)\r\n 337: - When it scales (level, time, area)\r\n 338: \r\n 339: Compare all scaling curves. Flag mismatches:\r\n 340: \r\n 341: ```\r\n 342: 鈿狅笍  Difficulty Curve Mismatch\r\n 343: combat.md: Enemy health scales exponentially with area (脳2 per area)\r\n 344: progression.md: Player damage scales linearly with level (+10% per level)\r\n 345: 鈫?By area 5, enemies have 32脳 base health; player deals ~1.5脳 base damage.\r\n 346:   The gap widens indefinitely. Late areas will become inaccessibly difficult\r\n 347:   unless the curves are reconciled.\r\n 348: ```\r\n 349: \r\n 350: ### 3f: Pillar Alignment\r\n 351: \r\n 352: Every system should clearly serve at least one design pillar. A system that\r\n 353: serves no pillar is \"scope creep by design\" 鈥?it's in the game but not in\r\n 354: service of what the game is trying to be.\r\n 355: \r\n 356: For each GDD system, check its Player Fantasy section against the design pillars.\r\n 357: Flag any system whose stated fantasy doesn't map to any pillar:\r\n 358: \r\n 359: ```\r\n 360: 鈿狅笍  Pillar Drift\r\n 361: fishing-system.md: Player Fantasy 鈥?\"peaceful, meditative activity\"\r\n 362: Pillars: \"Brutal Combat\", \"Tense Survival\", \"Emergent Stories\"\r\n 363: 鈫?The fishing system serves none of the three pillars. Either add a pillar\r\n 364:   that covers it, redesign it to serve an existing pillar, or cut it.\r\n 365: ```\r\n 366: \r\n 367: Also check anti-pillars 鈥?flag any system that does what an anti-pillar\r\n 368: explicitly says the game will NOT do:\r\n 369: \r\n 370: ```\r\n 371: 馃敶 Anti-Pillar Violation\r\n 372: Anti-Pillar: \"We will NOT have linear story progression 鈥?player defines their path\"\r\n 373: main-quest.md: Defines a 12-chapter linear story with mandatory sequence\r\n 374: 鈫?This system directly violates the defined anti-pillar.\r\n 375: ```\r\n 376: \r\n 377: ### 3g: Player Fantasy Coherence\r\n 378: \r\n 379: The player fantasies across all systems should be compatible 鈥?they should\r\n 380: reinforce a consistent identity for what the player IS in this game. Conflicting\r\n 381: player fantasies create identity confusion.\r\n 382: \r\n 383: ```\r\n 384: 鈿狅笍  Player Fantasy Conflict\r\n 385: combat.md: \"You are a ruthless, precise warrior 鈥?every kill is earned\"\r\n 386: dialogue.md: \"You are a charismatic diplomat 鈥?violence is always avoidable\"\r\n 387: exploration.md: \"You are a reckless adventurer 鈥?diving in without a plan\"\r\n 388: 鈫?Three systems present incompatible identities. Players will feel the game\r\n 389:   doesn't know what it wants them to be. Consider: do these fantasies serve\r\n 390:   the same core identity from different angles, or do they genuinely conflict?\r\n 391: ```\r\n 392: \r\n 393: ---\r\n 394: \r\n 395: ## Phase 4: Cross-System Scenario Walkthrough\r\n 396: \r\n 397: Walk through the game from the player's perspective to find problems that only\r\n 398: appear at the interaction boundary between multiple systems 鈥?things static\r\n 399: analysis of individual GDDs cannot surface.\r\n 400: \r\n 401: ### 4a: Identify Key Multi-System Moments\r\n 402: \r\n 403: Scan all GDDs and identify the 3鈥? most important player-facing moments where\r\n 404: multiple systems activate simultaneously. Look specifically for:\r\n 405: \r\n 406: - **Combat + Economy overlap**: killing enemies that drop resources, spending\r\n 407:   resources during combat, death/respawn interacting with economy state\r\n 408: - **Progression + Difficulty overlap**: level-up triggering mid-fight, ability\r\n 409:   unlocks changing combat viability, difficulty scaling at progression milestones\r\n 410: - **Narrative + Gameplay overlap**: dialogue choices locking/unlocking mechanics,\r\n 411:   story beats interrupting resource loops, quest completion triggering system\r\n 412:   state changes\r\n 413: - **3+ system chains**: any player action that triggers System A, which feeds\r\n 414:   into System B, which triggers System C (these are highest-risk interaction paths)\r\n 415: \r\n 416: List each identified scenario with a one-line description before proceeding.\r\n 417: \r\n 418: ### 4b: Walk Through Each Scenario\r\n 419: \r\n 420: For each scenario, step through the sequence explicitly:\r\n 421: \r\n 422: 1. **Trigger** 鈥?what player action or game event starts this?\r\n 423: 2. **Activation order** 鈥?which systems activate, in what sequence?\r\n 424: 3. **Data flow** 鈥?what does each system output, and is that output a valid\r\n 425:    input for the next system in the chain?\r\n 426: 4. **Player experience** 鈥?what does the player see, hear, or feel at each step?\r\n 427: 5. **Failure modes** 鈥?are there any of the following?\r\n 428:    - **Race conditions**: two systems trying to modify the same state simultaneously\r\n 429:    - **Feedback loops**: System A amplifies System B which re-amplifies System A\r\n 430:      with no cap or dampener\r\n 431:    - **Broken state transitions**: a system assumes a state that a previous\r\n 432:      system may have changed (e.g., \"player is alive\" assumption after a combat\r\n 433:      step that could have caused death)\r\n 434:    - **Contradictory messaging**: player receives conflicting feedback from two\r\n 435:      systems reacting to the same event (e.g., \"success\" sound + \"failure\" UI)\r\n 436:    - **Compounding difficulty spikes**: two systems both scaling up at the same\r\n 437:      progression point, multiplying the intended difficulty increase\r\n 438:    - **Reward conflicts**: two systems both reacting to the same trigger with\r\n 439:      rewards that together exceed the intended value (double-dipping)\r\n 440:    - **Undefined behavior**: the GDDs don't specify what happens in this combined\r\n 441:      state (neither system's rules cover it)\r\n 442: \r\n 443: ```\r\n 444: Example walkthrough:\r\n 445: Scenario: Player kills elite enemy at level-up threshold during active quest\r\n 446: \r\n 447: Trigger: Player lands killing blow on elite enemy\r\n 448: 鈫?combat.md: awards kill XP (100 pts)\r\n 449: 鈫?progression.md: XP total crosses level threshold 鈫?triggers level-up\r\n 450:   Output: new level, stat increases, ability unlock popup\r\n 451: 鈫?quest.md: kill-count criterion met 鈫?triggers quest completion event\r\n 452:   Output: quest reward XP (500 pts), completion fanfare\r\n 453: 鈫?progression.md (again): quest XP added 鈫?triggers SECOND level-up in same frame\r\n 454:   鈿狅笍  Data flow issue: quest.md awards XP without checking if a level-up\r\n 455:   is already in progress. progression.md has no guard against concurrent\r\n 456:   level-up events. Undefined behavior: does the player level up once or twice?\r\n 457:   Does the ability popup fire twice? Does the second level use the updated or\r\n 458:   pre-update stat baseline?\r\n 459: ```\r\n 460: \r\n 461: ### 4c: Flag Scenario Issues\r\n 462: \r\n 463: For each problem found during the walkthrough, categorize severity:\r\n 464: \r\n 465: - **BLOCKER**: undefined behavior, broken state transition, or contradictory\r\n 466:   player messaging 鈥?the experience is broken or incoherent in this scenario\r\n 467: - **WARNING**: compounding spikes, feedback loops without caps, reward conflicts 鈥?  the experience works but produces unintended outcomes\r\n 468: - **INFO**: minor ordering ambiguity or messaging overlap 鈥?worth noting but\r\n 469:   unlikely to cause player-visible problems\r\n 470: \r\n 471: Add all findings to the output report under **\"Cross-System Scenario Issues\"**.\r\n 472: Each finding must cite: the scenario name, the specific systems involved, the\r\n 473: step where the issue occurs, and the nature of the failure mode.\r\n 474: \r\n 475: ---\r\n 476: \r\n 477: ## Phase 5: Output the Review Report\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
